# Auto Mode

Auto mode lets the {{ROLE_TERM}} chain the lifecycle modes autonomously toward a goal, inside hard safety boundaries. The most common use is an autonomous research campaign that loops Design, Implement, Experiment, and Analyze until a budget expires. Auto mode never edits existing project files in place.

## 1. Trigger

Use Auto mode when {{USER_NAME}} asks to explore autonomously, to improve {{PROJECT_NAME}} for a time budget, to run experiments for N minutes or hours, or for a prompt that keeps researching until a budget expires. If the request only asks for a single next idea, use Design mode (`docs/operations/session-kickoff.md`) instead.

## 2. Which Modes Auto May Chain

| Chained mode | Risk | Rule |
|---|---|---|
| Investigate, Design, Analyze | low (read-only) | may run freely within the budget |
| Implement, Experiment | high (mutating + compute) | only inside an isolated workspace; never touch the originals |
| Write, Maintain | excluded | Auto does not autonomously rewrite prose or project docs; it returns proposals for review |

Auto inherits the strictest safety property of whatever it chains.

## 3. Responsibility Split

| Actor | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| {{USER_NAME}} | chooses the campaign intent, budget, and any preferred target |
| Claude Chat | reads current docs, designs the bounded campaign, writes the Claude Code prompt |
| Claude Code | creates an isolated workspace, copies source in, mutates only the copy, runs isolated experiments, logs outcomes, returns patch proposals |

Claude Chat must not hand off an open-ended "do research" prompt. It produces a bounded contract: scope, budget, comparison tier, logging, and stop conditions.

## 4. Workspace Isolation

All mutation happens under a task workspace; existing source, data, results, and runners stay read-only:

```text
${CLAUDE_DIR}/{TASK_ID}/
  workspace/src/
  runs/exp001/
  patches/best.patch
  outputs/results.jsonl
  outputs/campaign_summary.md
```

Copy the needed source into `workspace/src/` and never edit the originals. The final deliverable is a patch proposal plus evidence, not an in-place source edit.

## 5. Budget And Fair Comparison

Time controls when the campaign stops; the data subset, seed, and per-tier budget control fair comparison.

- The user-specified time is the campaign budget, not the per-experiment comparison unit.
- Experiments may be compared only within the same tier (a tier fixes the data subset, seed, budget, and metric parser).
- Promotion across tiers is allowed; a direct cross-tier comparison is not final evidence.

## 6. Evaluation Ladder

| Tier | Purpose | Typical scope |
|---|---|---|
| smoke | reject broken source quickly | import, grep, tiny dry-run checks |
| quick | catch obvious bad ideas | a small fixed subset, a short budget |
| full | candidate verdict evidence | the full subset, the full budget |

## 7. Keep, Discard, Promote

Each experiment gets exactly one decision: `crash` (failed; keep logs only), `discard` (worse than baseline in-tier), `keep_candidate` (promising, not yet full-tier evidence), `promote` (advances a tier), or `best_patch` (strongest patch at campaign end). Promotion criteria are fixed before the first run: a primary metric, one or more veto metrics, and a hard caution on per-case regression.

## 8. Result Logging

Every attempt appends one JSON object to `outputs/results.jsonl`:

```json
{
  "id": "exp001",
  "config": {"tier": "quick", "data_subset": "...", "seed": 42, "budget": "...", "changed_files": ["workspace/src/..."], "idea": "..."},
  "metrics": {"primary": null, "veto": null},
  "decision": "keep_candidate"
}
```

If a run crashes, metrics may be null, but the error summary and log path must be recorded.

## 9. Claude Code Prompt Contract

The handoff prompt includes: the canonical path-variable header from `docs/entrypoint.md` section 0; the budget and a stop margin; the target and candidate family; the active tier (data subset, seed, budget, metric parser); the workspace layout from section 4; read-only vs writable paths with source-copy steps; the keep/discard/promote criteria; the `results.jsonl` schema; the stop conditions; and the final deliverables. Use `docs/operations/prompt-factory.md` for the skeleton.

## 10. Stop Conditions

Stop and summarize when any fires: remaining time below the safety margin; {{USER_NAME}} interrupts; repeated crashes exceed the limit; no same-tier improvement after the attempt limit; required data or checkpoints missing; or the next tier cannot fit the remaining budget. Stopping is not failure; the required output is a faithful campaign summary with logs, patches, and the next recommended action.

## 11. Forbidden Actions

Auto mode must not: edit existing project files in place; run git commit or push against `{{PROJECT_VAR_BRACE}}`; use a test-label oracle for selection; revive a recorded rejected approach; hand-pick per-case hyperparameters to flatter a result; compare metrics across different tiers as final evidence; or overwrite existing results or checkpoints. Adopting a candidate into `{{PROJECT_VAR_BRACE}}` is a separate explicit task (it returns `patches/best.patch` and `outputs/campaign_summary.md`).
